  <tr>
   <td colspan="4" class="content">
    <pre>&lt;paulproteus&gt; There are two ways to solve that.
&lt;paulproteus&gt; 1) Someone just tries images until they stop working.
&lt;paulproteus&gt; 2) I try to read the nginx defaults and config, and then I try a
bunch of images until they stop working to make sure I guessed right.
&lt;paulproteus&gt; So I kind of am unenthusiastic about doing it myself, even though
I said I would.
&lt;paulproteus&gt; I think it's between 1 and 5 MB...
&lt;paulproteus&gt; The real problem, I guess, is that the user gets back a useless
nginx error (Request too large) rather than something helpful.
&lt;paulproteus&gt;
<a href="http://tag4.us/server/wordpressnginx-413-request-entity-too-large-error/">http://tag4.us/server/wordpressnginx-413-request-entity-too-large-error/</a> says
how to increase the max size
&lt;paulproteus&gt; Also we could create a custom HTTP 413 error page -- that would be
helpful.
&lt;paulproteus&gt; Anyone want to make such a page? You could totally probably find a
nice photo to put on it.
&lt;paulproteus&gt; It would look kinda like the Error 500 page, but its text would
say, "You sent us a request that was too large. Maybe you tried to upload an
image, but you uploaded something larger than we can handle. Hit back, and give
us something smaller instead."
&lt;paulproteus&gt; And it could have a picture like
<a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/annathered/3087624723/">http://www.flickr.com/photos/annathered/3087624723/</a> on it.
&lt;paulproteus&gt; Maybe I'll email Devel and see if anyone wants to.
&lt;paulproteus&gt; And I'll say "max 1 MB" and test that.</pre>
   </td>
  </tr>
 
 
